Step 1: Connect your Terminal to the Cluster
AWS needs to know that your local kubectl command should talk to your new EKS cluster.

Open your terminal.

Run this command (replace the name and region with yours):

Bash
aws eks update-kubeconfig --region ap-south-1 --name etl-monitoring-cluster
Test it: kubectl get nodes. If you see your nodes, you are connected!

Step 2: Create the Grafana Pod (Using Helm)
In Kubernetes, we don't usually create a single "Pod" manually; we use a Helm Chart which creates the Pod, the Service, and the Deployment all at once.

Add Grafana Repo:

Bash
helm repo add grafana https://grafana.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update
Install Grafana:

Bash
# We create a namespace called 'monitoring' to keep things clean
kubectl create namespace monitoring

helm install my-grafana grafana/grafana \
  --namespace monitoring \
  --set service.type=LoadBalancer
Using service.type=LoadBalancer will give you a public URL to access Grafana.

Step 3: Connect CloudWatch Logs (The Permissions)
Now we must give that Grafana pod "permission" to read your AWS logs. We use IRSA (IAM Roles for Service Accounts).

Create an IAM Policy: Go to IAM Console > Policies > Create Policy. Use this JSON:

JSON
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Action": ["logs:DescribeLogGroups", "logs:StartQuery", "logs:GetQueryResults", "cloudwatch:GetMetricData"],
    "Resource": "*"
  }]
}
Name it GrafanaCloudWatchPolicy.

Create the Service Account: Run this command in your terminal. This "links" a Kubernetes user to an AWS IAM role:

Bash
eksctl create iamserviceaccount \
  --name grafana-sa \
  --namespace monitoring \
  --cluster etl-monitoring-cluster \
  --attach-policy-arn arn:aws:iam::<YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID>:policy/GrafanaCloudWatchPolicy \
  --approve
Step 4: Configure Grafana to use the "Service Account"
We need to tell the Grafana Pod to use that grafana-sa we just created.

Update your Grafana installation:

Bash
helm upgrade my-grafana grafana/grafana \
  --namespace monitoring \
  --set serviceAccount.create=false \
  --set serviceAccount.name=grafana-sa
Step 5: Setup the Failure Percentage Dashboard
Log in to Grafana: * Get your LoadBalancer URL: kubectl get svc -n monitoring

Get your password: kubectl get secret --namespace monitoring my-grafana -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 --decode ; echo

Add CloudWatch Data Source:

In Grafana: Connections > Data Sources > Add CloudWatch.

Auth Provider: Select AWS SDK Default.

Default Region: ap-south-1.

Create the Failure Panel:

Add a new Visualization.

Select Query Mode: CloudWatch Log
